# =============================================================================
# .gitignore for python-devcontainer
# =============================================================================
# Most of this file is the standard GitHub Python template (`uv init`
# scaffolds it). Patterns are kept even when this project doesn't currently
# use a given tool — the cost of a future-proof line is one comment, the
# cost of accidentally committing __pypackages__/ is a clean-up PR.
#
# Project-specific decisions documented below at:
#   • [uv.lock]              — section near "# UV" — DO commit it
#   • [.python-version]      — section near "# pyenv" — DO commit it
#   • [.vscode/]             — bottom of file — partially share
#   • [.omc/ / .zac/]        — bottom of file — never commit (per-session)


# Byte-compiled / optimized / DLL files
__pycache__/
*.py[codz]
*$py.class

# C extensions
*.so

# Distribution / packaging
.Python
build/
develop-eggs/
dist/
downloads/
eggs/
.eggs/
lib/
lib64/
parts/
sdist/
var/
wheels/
share/python-wheels/
*.egg-info/
.installed.cfg
*.egg
MANIFEST

# PyInstaller
#   Usually these files are written by a python script from a template
#   before PyInstaller builds the exe, so as to inject date/other infos into it.
*.manifest
*.spec

# Installer logs
pip-log.txt
pip-delete-this-directory.txt

# Unit test / coverage reports
htmlcov/
.tox/
.nox/
.coverage
.coverage.*
.cache
nosetests.xml
coverage.xml
*.cover
*.py.cover
*.lcov
.hypothesis/
.pytest_cache/
cover/

# Translations
*.mo
*.pot

# Django stuff:
*.log
local_settings.py
db.sqlite3
db.sqlite3-journal

# Flask stuff:
instance/
.webassets-cache

# Scrapy stuff:
.scrapy

# Sphinx documentation
docs/_build/

# PyBuilder
.pybuilder/
target/

# Jupyter Notebook
.ipynb_checkpoints

# IPython
profile_default/
ipython_config.py

# pyenv
#   Decision for THIS repo: COMMIT .python-version. It pins the Python
#   minor version we develop and CI against, ensuring uv resolves the
#   same managed interpreter for everyone. The default template comment
#   below says "ignore for libraries" — we are an application/template,
#   not a library, so the inverse applies.
# .python-version

# pipenv
# Pipfile.lock

# UV
#   Decision for THIS repo: COMMIT uv.lock. The lockfile pins exact
#   transitive versions of every dependency. Without committing it,
#   `uv sync` on different machines would resolve different versions
#   and you'd lose reproducibility — which is half the reason to use
#   a devcontainer in the first place. This is also why Fix-A
#   pre-commit hooks (calling `uv run --frozen`) work: they trust
#   uv.lock as the single source of truth.
# uv.lock

# poetry
# poetry.lock
# poetry.toml

# pdm
# pdm.lock
# pdm.toml
.pdm-python
.pdm-build/

# pixi
# pixi.lock
.pixi/*
!.pixi/config.toml

# PEP 582; used by e.g. github.com/David-OConnor/pyflow and github.com/pdm-project/pdm
__pypackages__/

# Celery stuff
celerybeat-schedule*
celerybeat.pid

# Redis
*.rdb
*.aof
*.pid

# RabbitMQ
mnesia/
rabbitmq/
rabbitmq-data/

# ActiveMQ
activemq-data/

# SageMath parsed files
*.sage.py

# Environments
#   Decision: ignore .venv/ even though `uv sync` deterministically
#   recreates it. Reason: shebangs in .venv/bin/* embed the absolute
#   build path (e.g. /workspaces/python-devcontainer/.venv/bin/python),
#   so a venv built in the container is broken on the host and vice
#   versa. Re-creating it on a fresh clone is one `uv sync` command.
.env
.envrc
.venv
env/
venv/
ENV/
env.bak/
venv.bak/

# Devcontainer bind-mount roots
#   Decision: ignore .devcontainer/volumes/ — this directory holds the
#   bind-mount sources for the dev container's caches and per-user state
#   (uv-managed Pythons, VS Code Server install + extensions, XDG cache
#   for ruff/pre-commit/ty/...). All contents are container-generated and
#   regenerable; none of it is source code.
#
#   Why bind mounts instead of named volumes (which wouldn't need a
#   .gitignore entry at all): named volumes carried their own UID/GID,
#   which collided with the host's UID via updateRemoteUserUID and
#   produced a cascade of permission-denied failures. Bind mounts inherit
#   the host UID for free. Trading "one .gitignore entry" for "no UID-
#   mismatch bug class" is overwhelmingly worth it. See the bind-mount
#   block in .devcontainer/docker-compose.yml for the full history.
.devcontainer/volumes/

# Spyder project settings
.spyderproject
.spyproject

# Rope project settings
.ropeproject

# mkdocs documentation
/site

# mypy
.mypy_cache/
.dmypy.json
dmypy.json

# Pyre type checker
.pyre/

# pytype static type analyzer
.pytype/

# Cython debug symbols
cython_debug/

# PyCharm
# .idea/

# Abstra
.abstra/

# Visual Studio Code
#   Decision for THIS repo: don't ignore the whole .vscode/ dir, but
#   selectively share .vscode/extensions.json (recommended extensions)
#   while ignoring per-user settings.json. The devcontainer's
#   `customizations.vscode.extensions` block already covers the
#   ESSENTIAL extensions; .vscode/extensions.json is for nice-to-haves
#   that don't warrant rebuilding the image.
# .vscode/
!.vscode/extensions.json
# Temporary file for partial code execution
tempCodeRunnerFile.py

# Ruff stuff:
.ruff_cache/

# PyPI configuration file
.pypirc

# Marimo
marimo/_static/
marimo/_lsp/
__marimo__/

# Streamlit
.streamlit/secrets.toml

# --- oh-my-claudecode session artifacts ------------------------------------
# Decision: never commit. OMC writes per-session state (logs, plan files,
# research notes) into .omc/ and .zac/. These are personal to a single
# Claude session, not shared project state. Committing them would mean
# every PR carries unrelated session diff noise. If the team ever wants
# shared OMC conventions, that'll be an explicit, separate design.
.omc/
.zac/
